candidates.abstract:
We study the relation between cognitive abilities and stockholding using the recent&#13;
Survey of Health, Ageing and Retirement in Europe (SHARE), which has detailed data on&#13;
wealth and portfolio composition of individuals aged 50+ in 11 European countries and&#13;
three indicators of cognitive abilities: mathematical, verbal fluency, and recall skills. We&#13;
 find that the propensity to invest in stocks is strongly associated with cognitive abilities,&#13;
 for both direct stock market participation and indirect participation through mutual&#13;
 funds and retirement accounts. Since the decision to invest in less information-intensive&#13;
assets (such as bonds) is less strongly related to cognitive abilities, we conclude that the&#13;
association between cognitive abilities and stockholding is driven by information&#13;
constraints, rather than by features of preferences or psychological traits.
